Waste classification education starts at Jilin Kindergarten.
On 27 March, a kindergarten in Jilin City, Jilin Province, conducted a garbage classification education course to teach young children to identify recyclable waste and other types of waste.
It is known that this is the first time that garbage is classified into local early childhood classes.
The nine departments of Jilin Province jointly issued the Work Programme for the Advancement of Local Urban Waste Classification.
In 2019, on the basis of the pilot of the compulsory classification of waste from living in Changchun City, the province decided to carry out the classification of waste from living in local cities.
The city of Jilin is one of them.
Through this event, we hope to achieve the results of the early childhood-led family, the kindergarten-led society and the promotion of environmental concepts.
The event was organized by Liu Li Xin, Executive Director of the International Kindergarten.
On the same day, the head of the park read an environmental initiative, hoping that the garbage would start with children.
After performing the low-carbon bees dance, the children group up to do a garbage sorting game.
The instructors also issued the "Recoverable" "Other Waste" label, advising the children to stick it to the trash can and make a video when they come home.
Liu Li Xin said that the kindergarten had been promoting the concept of low carbon and green environment, with regular environmental workshops.
Disaggregatable trash cans have been set up at the dump in the garden, where the type of input is indicated.
The teacher taught the kids what to do with recyclable garbage.
According to preliminary statistics, approximately 5.4652 million tons of municipal waste were generated in 2018 in Jilin province, all of which were placed in disposal sites.
Of these, 3,29.29 million tons were disposed of in sanitary landfills, 2,092 million tons were burned and 80.1 million tons were treated using integrated processes.
After many years of effort, all municipalities and counties in the province have the capacity to treat household waste harmlessly.
The Work Programme for the Disaggregated Management of Land-based Living Waste in the Province of Jilin, which has been published, clearly calls for further activities such as the classification of garbage into schools, educational materials, classes, etc., to strengthen interaction between students and parents through the creation of the work of garbage-classing songs, songs, comics, micro-videos, etc., with the effect of “education of a child, influencing a family, promoting a community and nurturing a new generation”.
