The Legislative Council of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region co-sponsored the bill against the United States of America and Hong Kong.
In a joint statement issued on 27 January, a member of the Legislative Council of the HKSAR expressed strong opposition to the passing of the Hong Kong Human Rights and Democracy Act 2019 by the Foreign Committee of the House of Representatives of the United States Congress.
This statement, co-sponsored by 40 formed members of Parliament, states that Hong Kong currently enjoys the rights conferred by the Basic Law of the HKSAR, including maintaining the status of free trade ports and separate customs zones, entering into and implementing bilateral and multilateral agreements in different areas of the economy, finance, shipping, trade, communications, tourism, culture and sports, as well as in the name of “Hong Kong, China”, for the purpose of trading, cooperating and developing relations with different countries and regions of the world.
These rights are not exercised by any foreign Government or legislature.
Hong Kong has always been committed to international agreements, international rules, laws and business ethics, and has engaged in numerous areas of cooperation with different countries and regions.
The statement stated that the adoption of the bill by the Foreign Committee of the House of Representatives of the United States was not necessary, but merely served as a means of brazen interference in Hong Kong ' s internal affairs and seeking political leverage for its agents in Hong Kong, as called for by its proxies.
