According to the European Times 26, the reform of immigration policy will be discussed next week in both houses of the French Parliament.
French President Marlon recently stated in this regard that France cannot “host everyone,” but at the same time seeks to “take everyone well.”
It was reported that Marklon was trying to find a compromise route in immigration matters to ease the upcoming debate.
In a recent interview with the General Assembly during its general debate in New York, the United States of America, Marlon expressed the hope that there would be a genuine “two-pronged” approach to immigration policy that would strike a balance between humanitarianism and efficiency.
Marlon said: “If France wishes to receive (immigrants) properly, it cannot accept all”.
The four priorities of the migration policy are: to grant asylum to refugees in need of protection as soon as possible; to promote the integration of migrants more efficiently; to receive and protect all immigrants entering French territory; and to resettle more efficiently those who have entered France illegally and are not suitable for stay.
Whether illegal immigrants should be protected by the “State Medical Assistance” (AME) system has been the subject of much discussion before.
Marklon indicated that he would like to be able to “assess” the system, but not to eliminate it, but to limit it.
Following that statement, the far-right leader of the “National League” Le Pen wrote that Marklon's statement was “no talk”.
Members of the right-wing Republican party, the President of the Senate, Rachel, also stated that immigration policies should be discussed in a “mitigated” but “realistic” manner, indirectly criticizing Marlon.
Senator Valao of the Left Socialist Party believes that France should “receive more and better” on the issue of immigration, and criticizes Mark Long for “playing” the subject.
Reports indicate that the new version of the Asylum and Immigration Act, which has been in place for one year, has led to differences within the ruling party, but at the same time has not been able to appease the right-wing opposition.
In the next general election in 2022, the topic of immigration policy will once again become the focus of the far right, and Marklon needs to do something about it, but at the same time at the risk of provoking left-wing elements within the ruling party.
It was reported that immigration policy would be debated in the lower house of the French National Assembly on 30 September and in the Senate on 2 October.
There are indications that China’s A share is on the way to a “back-to-back” wave, and that many listed companies have come forward to buy back their shares.
