In the past two months, the restoration of a large painting of the Sanctuary of the Queens of Tianjin Palace, a national focal point, was completed on 26 days and will be reopened during the national holiday.
The Queen's Landscape is a large, traditional mural that fully reflects the life of mother and father.
With the approval of the State authorities, Cai Changqui, the director of the Tianjin Folk Museum (the Queen's Palace), was created from 1991 to 1994.
It is known that this mural was painted on the walls of the Palace of Queens south and north, 32 metres long and 2.6 metres high, in two parts, with more than 30 stories of the late Queens, the sea and the fermentation of the sky, and 358 people recreated the life of their mother.
Cai Changqui explained that in recent years Tianjin had experienced heavy summer rains and dry winters, which “wet dry” had led to the fragmentation of the mural, which accounted for 60 per cent of the entire mural area.
In order to protect and save Mother ' s ancestral murals, the ancient cultural street council and Tianjin City Palace in the southern Kasai district of Tianjin city initiated the restoration of the palace and the interior mural.
The restoration project, which was awarded by Cai Changqui, brought together four prominent national painters.
The restoration work was based on the principle of `old as old', while the original murals were partially adjusted and additional repairs were made to areas where the murals were not perfect.
We have also made innovations and attempts in colours, materials, pen ink, etc.
After repair, the original mural style, spirituality, spirituality and artistic style was maintained.
Established in 1326, the Queen's Palace, formerly known as the Queen's Palace, has been refurbished many times. It is one of the oldest buildings in the city of Tianjin and one of the oldest temples in China's present age.
