Viet Nam Forum on Economic and Social Issues, 2019, in the province of Chengxiang
The Deputy Director of the Economic Committee of the National Assembly of Viet Nam, Nguyen Dejan, revealed that early this year, Viet Nam ' s economic and social development showed many new developments and continued growth.
The Forum focused on the economic and social issues highlighted in the first months of 2019 and proposed measures for economic and social development in late 2019 and 2020.
At the Forum, participants had an in-depth exchange of views and views on four themes: economic development in 2019 and the impact of selected FTAs; salient issues in the economy of Viet Nam in 2019; salient issues in the socio-cultural context of Viet Nam in 2019; and projections and proposals for the economic and social development of Viet Nam in 2020.
There was general agreement that global economic growth had slowed in the first months of 2019, with increased risks and challenges.
Trade frictions among major economies further shrunk global trade and investment.
The International Monetary Fund (IMF) concluded that, despite the uncertainty surrounding the global economy, where 70 per cent of the global economy ' s economies are at a standstill in growth, Viet Nam ' s economic development has made many encouraging gains, with a smooth macroeconomic performance, inflation being effectively controlled, and an average increase in the consumer price index of 2.64 per cent in the first half of 2019, the lowest in almost three years.
GDP grew by 6.76 per cent in the first half of 2019, down from 7.05 per cent in the same period last year, but the increase remains high compared to the same period in 2011-2017.
In predicting trends in Viet Nam ' s economic development from 2019 to 2020, the Deputy Director of the National Centre for Economic and Social Projections of Viet Nam, Dundeon, stated that the economy of Viet Nam had shown a high growth momentum in 2019 against the backdrop of the turmoil in the world economy.
By 2020, Viet Nam ' s macroeconomics are expected to remain largely stable, the implementation of FTAs will contribute to trade development, economic restructuring and business improvements will be further strengthened, and Viet Nam ' s external export activities will decline as a result of trade frictions.
There is therefore a need to strengthen the early warning mechanism for monitoring and forecasting, to proactively seek trade relief measures for Viet Nam ' s exports, to find opportunities to expand new export markets and to facilitate external exports of commodities such as agricultural and water products.
At the same time, inflation rates have been kept at a reasonable level, thereby promoting complementary industries and supporting the development of high-tech, organic and ecological agriculture.
