Makoto makes tea with a plastic bag!
According to Central, a recent study in Canada has found that a bag of plastic tea bags may release billions, or even billions, of plastic particles, significantly higher than a person's estimated total intake of microplastics, but there is no evidence to date that the ingestion of plastic particles poses a threat to humanity.
Researchers at McGill University in Canada have reportedly found that immersing plastic tea in an almost boiled hot water (95°C) would release about 11.6 billion plastic particles and 3.1 billion smaller nanoplastic particles into a cup.
This number is significantly higher than a person ' s estimated total intake of microplastics.
According to studies published earlier in 2019, at least 50,000 plastic particles are eaten annually by the general population, while the same amount of microplastics is inhaled.
It is known that the study was published in the Journal of Environmental Science and Technology, where researchers tested four different types of commercial plastic tea parcels at the Montereau Shop and Café, opened the tea pack, immersed the tea bag in almost boiling water for five minutes and analysed using electronic microscopes and spectrometers.
According to this study, they found that more than 11.6 billion plastic particles were released from a single tea bag, “a few orders of magnitude higher than the previous plastic load of other foods”.
It has been reported that most tea bags are made of natural fibre, but many brands made of natural fibres are still sealed with plastic.
Some of the branded tea bags are no longer paper-based and instead use plastics, which are the subject of testing by researchers.
Plastic particles are small fragments of plastics, defined by researchers as being in the range of 100 nm to 5 cm, produced mainly by the decomposition of plastic waste.
Researchers found traces of plastic particles in air, soil, rivers and the deepest trenches around the world, and found them in tap water, bottled water, seafood and beer.
For the first time in October 2018, researchers found plastic particles in human faeces samples from several countries in different regions of the globe.
In order to test the potential toxicity of plastic particles released from the tea pack, the Canadian research team placed daphnia in contaminated water and found that microplastics affected the behaviour of the daphnia and caused them to develop in a developmental malformations.
According to the World Health Organization (WHO), there is no evidence to date that plastic particles can pose a threat to humans.
However, WHO noted that more research was needed to fully understand how these plastics spread to the environment and what effects they had on humans.
Researchers speculate that these tea packages release large quantities of plastic particles, which may be in contact with boiling water, and even if “eating” plastics heat up to 40°C, they may break down or see some toxic substances.
