China issues China and the United Nations and reports on climate change and sustainable development - Xinhua Network
On 26 September, the Chinese delegation to the 74th session of the United Nations General Assembly officially published China and the United Nations - China's position paper for the 74th session of the United Nations General Assembly, the United Nations Climate Summit: China's position and action, China's Progress Report on the Implementation of the Sustainable Development Agenda 2030 (2019), and the Earth's Big Data to Support Sustainable Development Goals.
China and the United Nations - China's position paper for the 74th session of the United Nations General Assembly summarized the achievements and developments in China's cooperation with the United Nations in various fields in the 70 years since the establishment of the new China, particularly since the 18th Congress of the Party.
It was noted that the Chinese President, Xi Jinping, had proposed to promote the formation of a community of human destiny and had become the flag of diplomacy of China ' s major Powers.
Guided by Xi ' s diplomatic philosophy, China has taken a more active and active stance in international affairs, contributing more to world peace and development and assuming more responsibilities.
China has always been a builder of world peace, a contributor to global development and a guardian of the international order.
The document describes China ' s important contribution to the three pillars of the United Nations: peace, development and human rights.
Reaffirm China ' s firm support for multilateralism and its commitment to the central role of the United Nations in international affairs; note that China ' s development and the world ' s development are mutually reinforcing; and emphasize that, in the face of the major changes that have not occurred in the world for a century, a developing China will increasingly contribute positive energy to the world.
The United Nations Climate Action Summit: China ' s position and actions are closely linked to the nine major areas of action of the United Nations Climate Action Summit. China ' s policy advocacy for international cooperation to address climate change and China ' s achievements in combating climate change are described.
As the largest developing country in the world, China considers addressing climate change as an inherent requirement for its own sustainable development and as the responsibility for building a community of human destiny. It will continue to overcome the many difficult challenges to its own development, firmly uphold multilateralism, implement its international commitments and make every effort to promote the full and effective implementation of the Paris Agreements.
China ' s Progress Report on the Implementation of the Sustainable Development Agenda 2030 (2019) is the second progress report issued by China following the launch of the Implementation Progress Report in 2017.
The report provides a comprehensive overview of China ' s initiatives, progress, challenges and next steps in the implementation of the 2030 agenda. It demonstrates China ' s determination and achievements in implementing the new concept of development and achieving high-quality development.
The cases contained in the report, such as precise graduation from poverty, innovation-led development, ecological civilization-building, rural renewal and the building of a “one-way path”, would provide useful lessons for other countries in implementing the 2030 agenda.
The report on Big Earth Data underpinning the Sustainable Development Goals demonstrates China ' s exploration and practice of using Big Earth data to support the implementation of Agenda 2030 and policy decision-making. It reveals the value and prospects of technologies and methodologies for monitoring and assessing sustainable development goals. It provides new perspectives and support to the international community to fill data and methodological gaps and accelerate the implementation of Agenda 2030.
