United States electronic smoke has claimed 12 lives and the associated lung damage reached 805.
According to Central, on 26 local time, United States health officials stated that 12 people had died of electronic smoke-related diseases in the United States and that there were 805 cases of lung damage associated with electronic smoke.
It was reported that the United States Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) had notified these figures and indicated that specific substances causing the disease had not been identified.
However, most patients reported the use of electronic smoke products containing tetrahydrocannabinol, the main compound in cannabis that affects mental health.
The proliferation of lung cases is known to be associated with the purchase of contaminated electronic smoke detectors on the black market.
According to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, the above-mentioned 12 deaths occurred in 10 states from California to Florida, and the related 805 confirmed and suspected cases were reported by 46 states and the United States Virgin Islands.
Over the past three weeks, sales of electronic smoke have been banned in India and Massachusetts, and in New York and Michigan.
According to reports, the Trump Government intends to ban all e-smoking products other than tobacco from October.
