The Commission stated that Ms. Gail Ayton's boss, who had worked at Wagga Wagga's store for more than 20 years, Jianbin Wang, translated it in English by Eddie, treated her employees “extremely unfair” and could violate anti-discrimination laws.
Ms. Ayton told the Committee that Mr. Wang had taken over the store in 2016 and that he had been “wanted to fire me”, because she was not Chinese.
In this case, the Vice-Chairman of the Commission, Peter Sams, conducted a search on the Internet and found “a number of job advertisements previously issued by Mr. Wang at various Australian Chinese employment forums”.
Among the job requirements listed for these positions is one that says "Present Asian woman" and the other that "Present Asian employee".
The third post says that he “will prefer people abroad (sic)”.
Mr. Wang fired Ms. Ayton by text message in April of this year, later claiming that this was due to her absence from work and to a small cash shortage allegedly occurring on the cash register ranging from $5.10 to $30.
