He should consider paying compensation to Ms. Ayton, a casual worker with an hourly salary of $26.
In view of the possible violation of anti-discrimination and labour relations legislation, Sams indicated that he would submit his decisions and documents to the Committee to consider whether Mr. Wang ' s actions should be referred to other bodies to investigate possible violations of state or federal law.
He states that Mr. Wang did not give Ms. Ayton any opportunity to respond to the alleged reasons for her dismissal.
He said: “I believe that an irremediably unfair and biased procedure should be adopted to dismiss the applicant, and Mr. Wang has the opportunity to “wait”, which he believes would `prove' the termination of the applicant's employment. It's not like it's a bad idea.
“He is wrong ... the defence should have completely ignored any natural and fair treatment given to the applicant when dismissing her, and it is alarming that he acted in an indecent and grossly unjust manner. It's not like it's a bad idea.
Mr. Sams stated that, although Foodworks was a small business, “it must be said frankly that no decent employer would dismiss an employee in the most unfair and perfunctory manner recognized in this case. It's not like it's a bad idea.
