Study: The national healthy diet index in the United States has grown slightly, but it is still challenging - the new medium net.
On September 27, China Newsnet reported that in recent days, a recent study in the United States has shown that the United States government has seen a modest increase in its healthy diet index from 56 to 58.
But when the score is 100, it is not a celebration.
American nationals continue to face “significant challenges” in their diet.
One of the authors of the study, Dr. Zhang Fongfan, a nutrition researcher at Tafts University, Massachusetts, stated that Americans continue to consume too much food that could cause diseases such as heart disease, diabetes and obesity, which are the most common diseases of American nationals.
The study was published in the Journal of the American Medical Association on 24th.
The study was based on the findings of a health survey of 44,000 adults conducted by the United States Government between 1999 and 2016.
The authors wrote that “Despite considerable improvement, significant dietary challenges remain”.
These challenges are known to include reducing United States nationals ' consumption of food containing saturated fats, such as snacks, hot dogs, fat cattle and butter.
The study found that the intake of these unhealthy fats in people ' s daily diet increased from 11.5 per cent to 12 per cent, exceeding the recommended 10 per cent intake limit.
The biggest improvement in American diets is that the sugar intake dropped from 16% to about 14%, but the intake is still too high.
Officially, sugar-added intake should be less than 10% in the daily diet.
With regard to the reasons for the decline in sugar intake, researchers consider it to be related to the decrease in the consumption of sweet soda, but Zhang Fang emphasizes that sugar is often added to even less sweet foods, such as yoghurt and ketchup.
There has been a slight increase in adult consumption of fruits, nuts, oats and other whole- grain categories in the United States.
However, data for 2016 indicate that these foods still account for less than 5 per cent of daily diets.
Despite a slight decrease in salt intake and a reduction in drinking juice leading to low-quality carbohydrates intake, Zhang Fang indicates that they still account for as much as 42 per cent of the daily calorie, many of which come from refined white bread and other refined grains.
The study is based on biennial personal health surveys that remind adults of the food they have eaten in the last 24 hours.
These health surveys have asked the question twice every few days since 2003.
The government’s Food Guide for American Residents recommends “a healthy diet” to reduce the risk of chronic disease.
The guide points out that people should consume more nutritious foods, such as vegetables, fruits, whole grains, low-fat dairy products, and seafood, skinny meat, poultry meat, eggs, seed foods that can provide protein.
During the study period, the number of people suffering from diabetes almost doubled, to over 7%, and obesity increased over many years – today about 70% of all Americans are overweight or obese.
In addition, heart disease remains the leading cause of death among United States nationals.
