The Dubai Expo in 2020 released mascots.
The 2020 Dubai Expo mascot launch ceremony was held in Dubai, United Arab Emirates.
The mascot consists of six cartoon images, including two UAE children, three flying robots and a UAE tree with beans.
The launch presented the viewer with information on six mascots through video clips.
9-year-old Rashid and 8-year-old Latifa are brothers and sisters representing the people of the Emirates.
Three robots correspond to the three sub-themes of the Expo, blue robots represent “mobility”, green robots represent “sustainability”, yellow robots represent “opportunities”.
An old bean tree, named "Salamar", is the "old grandmother" of five "little children" and symbolizes the ancestors who protected the land.
Ahmed, Chairman of the Dubai World Expo High Council, said that mascots can strengthen emotional ties between large-scale events and participants, “believing that the mascot of Dubai World Expo will convey the traditional spirit of storytelling, show the creativity of indigenous talent, and express our ambitions and expectations.”
The launch was attended by the Vice-President and Prime Minister of the United Arab Emirates, Sheikh Mohammed Dubai, Crown Prince Hamdan of Dubai, the Minister of State for International Cooperation of the United Arab Emirates, and the Director of the Dubai World Bureau, Lim Hashimi.
The Dubai Expo will be held in Dubai from 20 October 2020 to 10 April 2021 under the theme “Communication of ideas for the future”.
This will be the first time that the Expo will be held in the Middle East.
Starting next year, Chinese students can apply for German undergraduate studies with their high grades.
In recent days, the Anabin database of Germany, which is responsible for certifying foreign academic qualifications, has been announced on the official web: starting in 2020, Chinese high school graduates can apply directly for undergraduate studies at German universities on the basis of their high-level qualifications, without having to enrol in domestic universities.
Prior to this, Chinese high school graduates applying for a university in Germany had to study undergraduate studies in the country for one semester (211,985) or three semesters (general undergraduate studies), and had passed the APS review or the TeestAS examination.
The issuance of the new regulations may save at least six months for Chinese students who wish to study in Germany.
It was informed that the new regulations would enter into force in the second half of 2019.
Applicants are required to complete 12 years of regular compulsory education and obtain a high school diploma, to take the examination, to pass the examination, and to achieve 70 per cent and above of the total score (more than 525 if the score is 750), and to include the requirements of two languages and one mathematics or natural sciences.
In addition, specific professional requirements for the achievement of advanced examinations vary.
For example, applying for specializations such as medicine, oral medicine, veterinary medicine, pharmacology, etc., requires 80% of the full score for advanced examinations and must include at least two in mathematics, physics, chemistry, biology, or participation in general; applying for legal studies requires 80% of the full score for advanced examinations, and advanced examinations must include foreign languages, history, at least two in geography, or participation in general.
According to incomplete statistics, China ' s high-level examination has been endorsed by a number of countries, including Germany, the United Kingdom, Canada and Australia.
In the case of the United Kingdom, universities such as Cambridge University, Birmingham University and Lester University have accepted applications from Chinese students for higher education.
