Journalists learned on 27 January from the Yunnan Academy of Agricultural Sciences that the green moths in Yunnan grassland were being effectively protected from widespread outbreaks and that the prevention and control efforts had produced milestones.
In January this year, for the first time ever, the town of Yunnan Pum Mae County discovered grassland night moths that had been moved from abroad, which were subsequently confirmed in 129 Yunnan counties, and gradually spread from Yunnan to mainland China, posing a direct threat to Chinese food production.
Grassland night moths are important agricultural pests originating in the tropics and subtropical regions of the Americas that are food-rich and remote flight and are significant flight pests of the FAO Global Early Warning System, characterized by “internationality, flightability, outbreak and destruction”.
The pest endangers more than 80 crops, such as maize, sugar cane and sorghum, and can produce as much as 70 per cent of the food.
The difficulty of combating the disease is such that China does not have a registered pesticide to combat the disease.
Since the grassland night moths moved into Yunnan, the Yunnan Academy of Agricultural Sciences has selected Eedong Research Fellows to lead the Yunnan Academy of Agricultural Sciences ' cross-border harmful organisms in agriculture, in collaboration with the Green Control and Control Provincial Innovation Team, to a line, field surveys, sample collection and technical guidance and pilot demonstration.
The team has acquired initial knowledge of the species characteristics of night moths in the Yunnan herbs, the natural insect resources, the origin characteristics of the insects outside the country, the migration trajectory of the population, the poison and the effects of field control.
They have been actively engaged in research and application of green-control technologies, which have achieved over 90 per cent of the control effects in the demonstration areas through the implementation of new green-control technologies such as stock monitoring, insect booby traps, scientific medicines and agronomic measures, while reducing the use of chemical pesticides, protecting natural enemy resources and the ecological environment, and providing technical safeguards for Yunnan to effectively control the eruption of grassland night moths and sustainable governance.
At present, moths in Yunnan grassland are effectively protected from large-scale outbreaks and control efforts have produced milestones.
As a next step, the Yunnan Academy of Agricultural Sciences will focus on the ecological mechanisms of stock migrations and invasions, which will go beyond the construction of biological control and green technology systems.
At the same time, international cross-border cooperation has been actively promoted with a view to establishing joint priority laboratories and joint monitoring sites and demonstration areas outside the country in order to enhance the full range of surveillance and early warning capabilities of night moths in Yunnan grasslands.
