New regulations for consultation: Qualification of social capital for rural land ownership
Qualification of social capital for rural land ownership
The Rural Land Management Scheme is open to comment.
Yesterday, the Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Affairs website published a public consultation notice on the Rural Land Management Scheme (revised draft for comments) (hereinafter referred to as the Opinion), which increased the regulation and risk prevention of the transfer of social capital flows, such as business enterprises, to land ownership.
The draft opinion is now open to public consultation.
According to the Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Development, in order to implement the newly amended Rural Land Contracting Act, to further consolidate and improve the basic rural business system, to deepen the reform of the rural land system, and to implement the “triple-ownership” system, the Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Development has revised the Rural Land Contracting and Transfer Management Scheme, resulting in a draft opinion.
The Beijing Youth Reporter learned of several important changes to the draft opinion first published.
The newly amended Rural Land Contracting Act, which defines the scope of land transfers, introduces the concept of “triple power-sharing” with separate sections on “land contracting rights” and “land management rights”, and makes a clear distinction between land contracting rights transfer, swaps and land transfer rights (rent, subcontract, shareholding or other).
In this Draft Opinion, in order to implement the concept of “triple power sharing”, to respond effectively to the main thrust of the reform of the Rural Land Contracting Act and to take into account the wide differences in the transfer of land ownership and the transfer of rights to land contracting, in terms of parties, procedures, regulations, etc., this revision defines the scope of the transfer, focusing on the transfer of rights to land, including through leasing, equity, etc., by changing the name of the regulation from the Rural Land Contracting and Management Scheme to the Rural Land Management Transfer Scheme.
The transfer and swap of land contracting rights will be regulated separately.
According to the draft opinion, in the context of the “triple power sharing”, farmers are only entitled to a limited period of land ownership.
Theoretically, even in the event of liquidation, farmers risk losing their business rights for a certain period of time, and thus providing for the return of the place of contract to the original contractor is no longer legally necessary and is in conflict with the Insolvency Act.
In response to farmers ' risk of land loss, methods such as preferential shares, rentals and buy-backs have emerged in practice.
Taking into account that priority shares are more well developed theoretically explored in corporate law, they are recommended as advocacy provisions to protect against the risk of stock loss.
